The duplicates of similar writs made in the Curia were brought into the Exchequer when it sat, by the ‘Clericus Constabularie' (see I. vi. D, below). The writ quoted by Madox (p. 268) and referred to above is cited by him ‘Ex rescripto Autographi in Archiuis Turris Londoniae.' The document he saw was accordingly such a contrabreue preserved in the Chancery. Many instances will be found of the preparation of contrabreuia in the printed Close Rolls of the reign of Henry 111, from which it appears that at that date contrabreuz'a were only made of the writs to accountants which they would naturally produce at the Exchequer‚ not of writs to the treasurer or barons.
